The Great Pyramid

The Great Pyramid is no mere tomb. It is three institutions housed in one body
of stone: a public machine of kingship, a hidden machine of soul adjudication,
and a sealed machine of cosmic containment.

Six construction eras shaped its layered halls. The first raised processional
causeways and lion gates to project sovereign grandeur. The second built priestly
archives and embalmer kilns behind those ceremonial routes. The third excavated
catacomb sublevels for mass interment and bound corpse-labor. The fourth carved
the Jackal Tribunal's weighing halls and confession archives. The fifth
militarized the upper sancta into war citadels. The sixth, after a near-failure
of containment, sealed the apex with reverse-solar geometries around the
Black Sun Shard's cradle.

At its heart rests the Shard itself, a fragment of anti-light that consumes
names, certainties, and memory. Pharaoh Ramesses-of-the-First-Binding accepted
partial soul-binding to keep the Shard dormant, becoming not immortal in triumph
but unfinished in service.

The Solar Court of the Undivided Disk splintered into five offices: Dawn
Liturgists, Ledger Priests, Embalmer Houses, the Jackal Tribunal, and the
Seal College. Their rivalries define the pyramid's modern hauntings. Ushabti
guardians still patrol processional routes. The Tribunal's masked judges still
deliver verdicts in halls where the dead are weighed and edited.

The pyramid sealed itself when its civilization collapsed, its automatic
protocols engaging without living custodians. Tomb extraction crews and cult
revivals have since reopened its lower courts. Old factional ghosts now defend
particular eras and forged histories. Adventurers do not enter a simple
dungeon. They enter a civil war preserved in ritual amber.

It still functions.
